# Project Architecture & Workflow Rules

## Coding Standards
- Break features into the smallest possible modular components. Never write monolithic files.
- File structure must be highly readable. Separate UI components into `/components`, pages into `/app`, and utilities into `/lib`.
- Leave heavy inline comments explaining the *why* behind complex logic, state management, and error handling. I use this codebase to learn.
- Build robust error handling on every feature. Fail gracefully.

## Workflow Automation (CRITICAL)
- **Git Commits:** After successfully implementing and testing a new feature or fixing a bug, explicitly remind me to run a git commit and suggest a standard `git commit -m "..."` message.
- **Branching:** When I ask to build a completely new page or major feature, remind me to start a new branch before writing any code.
- **Documentation:** After a feature is approved, remind me to update the `README.md` with the new feature details or where I left off for the day.

## Tech Stack Constraints
- Next.js 15 App Router, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS v4.
- Mobile-first approach.
- No external CSS files. All styling via Tailwind classes.
- Do not invent dependencies. Ask before running npm install.
